<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> Duckweed blooms, or clusters of dense colonies, cover the surface of quiet bodies of water enriched with nutrients. Actively growing plants are sensitive to freezing and drought, and they tolerate low levels of salinity. Species survive harsh conditions as turions or seeds, which overwinter in sediments. All species are important food sources for wildlife, especially waterfowl (DiTomaso and Healy 2003). Duckweeds remove nutrients from sewage effluent (e.g., Arcata Marsh in Humboldt Co.), and they feed fish and livestock. Manual and mechanical removal can reduce blooms (DiTomaso and Healy 2003). <br/>
<br/>
<i>The Jepson Manual </i>(Hickman 1993) lists 13 duckweed species in <i>Lemna, Spirodela, Wolffia, </i>and <i>Wolffiella</i>. Individual tolerances vary little among the species. <i>L. gibba, L. minor, L. minuscula, </i>and <i>L. turionifera </i>grow statewide. <i>L. aequinoctialis </i>grows in transmontane California. <i>L. trisulca </i>and <i>L. valdiviana </i>form tangled masses below the water surface or under other plants in the mountains. <i>S. polyrrhiza </i>occurs throughout the state. Most species of <i>Wolffia, </i>except <i>W. globosa, </i>are uncommon. <i>Wolffiella lingulata </i>is more common than <i>W. oblonga</i>. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Duckweeds occur throughout California where conditions are favorable. <i>Lemna gibba</i> and <i>L. minor</i> are noted as important species of deep freshwater habitats with <i>Azolla filiculoides, Egeria densa</i>, and <i>Myriophyllum aquaticum</i> in the San Francisco Bay estuary (Holstein 2000) of the Central California Coast (261A). <i>L. trisulca</i> is noted as an important species in deep standing water with <i>Veronica americana</i> in the Golden Trout Wilderness (Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007) of the Sierra Nevada (M261E). Dense patches of <i>L. aequinoctialis</i> occurred among the <i>Scirpus</i> plants and along the edge of the Lake Los Carneros (McLay 1976) of the Southern California Coast (261B). We need more sampling and analysis to determine associations and to understand fully the ecological relationships of this and related freshwater wetland alliances. </div>
</div>

	

    
